# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: level-shifters
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:level-shifters/level-shifter] Modern systems use level shifters to bridge domains between processors, logic, sensors, and other circuits.
[src:level-shifters/level-shifter] In recent years, the three most common logic levels have been 1.8V, 3.3V, and 5V, though levels above and below these voltages are also used.
[src:level-shifters/level-shifter] Uni-directional – All input pins are dedicated to one voltage domain, all output pins are dedicated to the other.
[src:level-shifters/level-shifter] Bi-directional with Dedicated ports – Each voltage domain has both input and output pins, but the data direction of a pin does not change.
[src:level-shifters/level-shifter] Bi-directional with external direction indicator – When an external signal is changed, inputs become outputs and vice versa.
[src:level-shifters/level-shifter] Bi-directional, auto-sensing – A pair of I/O spanning voltage domains can act as either inputs or outputs depending on external stimulus without the need for a dedicated direction control pin.
[src:level-shifters/level-shifter] Fixed function level shifter ICs - These ICs provide several different types of level shift in fixed function devices.
[src:level-shifters/level-shifter] Often lumped into 2-bit, 4-bit, or 8-bit level shift configurations offered with various VDD1 and VDD2 ranges, these devices translate logic levels without any additional integrated logic or timing adjustment.
[src:level-shifters/level-shifter] Configurable mixed-signal ICs (CMICs) – Level shifter circuitry can also be implemented in a CMIC.
[src:level-shifters/level-shifter] The no-code programmable nature of CMICs allows designers to implement fully customizable level shifters with the added option to integrate configurable logic or timing adjustments in the same device.
[src:level-shifters/level-shifter] Power Management ICs realize level shifters using differential signaling.
[src:level-shifters/level-shifter] The differential pair steers the current in one of its two legs which then drives a latch in a different voltage domain and level shifts the voltage.
[src:level-shifters/level-shifter] Since level shifters are used to resolve the voltage incompatibility between various parts of a system, they have a wide range of applications as well.
[src:level-shifters/level-shifter] Level shifters are widely used in interfacing legacy devices and also in SD cards, SIM cards, CF cards, audio codecs and UARTs.
[src:level-shifters/level-shifter] Level shifters are also widely used in gate driver circuits used in power management ICs.
[src:level-shifters/level-shifter] In these applications, level shifter translates the control logic signal to high voltages used in driving power MOSFETs.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] Before the widespread use of integrated circuits, various solid-state and vacuum-tube logic systems were used but these were never as standardized and interoperable as the integrated-circuit devices.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] The most common logic family in modern semiconductor devices is metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) logic, due to low power consumption, small transistor sizes, and high transistor density.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] The families RTL, DTL, and ECL were derived from the logic circuits used in early computers, originally implemented using discrete components.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] One example is the Philips NORBIT family of logic building blocks.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] The PMOS and I2L logic families were used for relatively short periods, mostly in special purpose custom large-scale integration circuits devices, and are generally considered obsolete.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] For example, early digital clocks or electronic calculators may have used one or more PMOS devices to provide most of the logic for the finished product.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] The F-14 Central Air Data Computer, Intel 4004, Intel 4040, and Intel 8008 microprocessors and their support chips were PMOS.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] Of these families, only ECL, TTL, NMOS, CMOS, and BiCMOS are currently still in widespread use.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] ECL is used for very high-speed applications because of its price and power demands, while NMOS logic is mainly used in VLSI circuits applications such as CPUs and memory chips which fall outside of the scope of this article.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] Present-day "building block" logic gate ICs are based on the ECL, TTL, CMOS, and BiCMOS families.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] Class of digital circuits built using resistors as the input network and bipolar junction transistors (BJTs) as switching devices.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] The Atanasoff–Berry Computer used resistor-coupled vacuum tube logic circuits similar to RTL.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] Several early transistorized computers (e.g., IBM 1620, 1959) used RTL, where it was implemented using discrete components.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] A family of simple resistor–transistor logic integrated circuits was developed at Fairchild Semiconductor for the Apollo Guidance Computer in 1962.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] Texas Instruments soon introduced its own family of RTL.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] A variant with integrated capacitors, RCTL, had increased speed, but lower immunity to noise than RTL.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] This was made by Texas Instruments as their "51XX" series.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] Class of digital circuits in which the logic gating function (e.g., AND) is performed by a diode network and the amplifying function is performed by a transistor.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] Diode logic was used with vacuum tubes in the earliest electronic computers in the 1940s including ENIAC.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] Diode–transistor logic (DTL) was used in the IBM 608, which was the first all-transistorized computer.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] Early transistorized computers were implemented using discrete transistors, resistors, diodes and capacitors.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] The first diode–transistor logic family of integrated circuits was introduced by Signetics in 1962.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] DTL was also made by Fairchild and Westinghouse.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] A family of diode logic and diode–transistor logic integrated circuits was developed by Texas Instruments for the D-37C Minuteman II Guidance Computer in 1962, but these devices were not available to the public.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] A variant of DTL called "high-threshold logic" incorporated Zener diodes to create a large offset between logic 1 and logic 0 voltage levels.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] These devices usually ran off a 15 volt power supply and were found in industrial control, where the high differential was intended to minimize the effect of noise.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] P-type MOS (PMOS) logic uses p-channel MOSFETs to implement logic gates and other digital circuits.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] PMOS logic dominated industry approximately from 1960 to 1970.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] N-type MOS (NMOS) logic uses n-channel MOSFETs to implement logic gates and other digital circuits.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] These were the driving principles in the design of NMOS logic, which uses n-channel MOSFETs exclusively.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] However, neglecting leakage current, NMOS logic consumes power even when no switching is taking place, unlike CMOS logic.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] The MOSFET invented at Bell Labs between 1955 and 1960 had both pMOS and nMOS devices with a 20 μm process.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] Their original MOSFET devices had a gate length of 20 μm and a gate oxide thickness of 100 nm.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] However, the nMOS devices were impractical, and only the pMOS type were practical working devices.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] A more practical NMOS process was developed several years later.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] NMOS was initially faster than CMOS, thus NMOS was more widely used for computers in the 1970s.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] With advances in technology, CMOS logic displaced NMOS logic in the mid-1980s to become the preferred process for digital chips.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] 1961 IBM invented ECL (also known as current-mode logic (CML)) as current steering logic for use in the transistorized IBM 7030 Stretch computer, where it was implemented using discrete components.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] In 1962 Motorolla introduced their first line of ECL integrated circuit devices referred to as *MECL 10000.* MECL required negative power supply.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] A subsequent development of ECL using positive-supply includes later *PECL* and *LVPECL*.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] ECL uses an overdriven bipolar junction transistor (BJT) differential amplifier with single-ended input and limited emitter current.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] In TTL logic, bipolar junction transistors (BJTs) perform the logic and amplifying functions.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] The first transistor–transistor logic family of integrated circuits was introduced by Sylvania as *Sylvania Universal High–Level Logic* (SUHL) in 1963.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] Texas Instruments introduced the 7400 series TTL family in 1964.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] Transistor–transistor logic uses bipolar transistors to form its integrated circuits.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] TTL has changed significantly over the years, with newer versions replacing the older types.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] Since the transistors of a standard TTL gate are saturated switches, minority carrier storage time in each junction limits the switching speed of the device.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] Variations on the basic TTL design are intended to reduce these effects and improve speed, power consumption, or both.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] Schottky formulated a theory predicting the **Schottky effect**, which led to the Schottky diode and later Schottky transistors.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] For the same power dissipation, Schottky transistors have a faster switching speed than conventional transistors because the Schottky diode prevents the transistor from saturating and storing charge; see Baker clamp.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] Logic gates built with Schottky transistors switch faster than TTL gates built with ordinary BJTs but consume more power.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] With **Low-power Schottky** (LS), internal resistance values were increased to reduce power consumption and increase switching speed over the original version.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] The introduction of **Advanced Low-power Schottky** (ALS) further increased speed and reduced power consumption.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] A faster logic family called **FAST** (Fairchild Advanced Schottky TTL) (Schottky) (F) was also introduced that was faster than original Schottky TTL.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] CMOS logic gates use complementary arrangements of enhancement-mode N-channel and P-channel field effect transistor.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] Since the initial devices used oxide-isolated metal gates, they were called **CMOS** (complementary metal–oxide–semiconductor logic).
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] In contrast to TTL, CMOS uses almost no power in the static state (that is, when inputs are not changing).
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] A CMOS gate draws no current other than leakage when in a steady 1 or 0 state.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] When the gate switches states, current is drawn from the power supply to charge the capacitance at the output of the gate.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] This means that the current draw of CMOS devices increases with switching rate (controlled by clock speed, typically).
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] The first CMOS family of logic integrated circuits was introduced by RCA as *CD4000 COS/MOS*, the 4000 series, in 1968.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] Initially CMOS logic was slower than LS-TTL.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] However, because the logic thresholds of CMOS were proportional to the power supply voltage, CMOS devices were well-adapted to battery-operated systems with simple power supplies.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] CMOS gates can also tolerate much wider voltage ranges than TTL gates because the logic thresholds are (approximately) proportional to power supply voltage, and not the fixed levels required by bipolar circuits.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] The required silicon area for implementing such digital CMOS functions has rapidly shrunk.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] VLSI technology incorporating millions of basic logic operations onto one chip, almost exclusively uses CMOS.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] The extremely small capacitance of the on-chip wiring caused an increase in performance by several orders of magnitude.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] On-chip clock rates as high as 4 GHz have become common, approximately 1000 times faster than the technology by 1970.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] CMOS chips often work with a broader range of power supply voltages than other logic families.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] Early TTL ICs required a power supply voltage of 5V, but early CMOS could use 3 to 15V.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] Lowering the supply voltage reduces the charge stored on any capacitances and consequently reduces the energy required for a logic transition.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] Reduced energy implies less heat dissipation.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] The energy stored in a capacitance *C* and changing *V* volts is ½ *CV*2.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] By lowering the power supply from 5V to 3.3V, switching power was reduced by almost 60 percent (power dissipation is proportional to the square of the supply voltage).
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] Many motherboards have a voltage regulator module to provide the even lower power supply voltages required by many CPUs.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] Because of the incompatibility of the CD4000 series of chips with the previous TTL family, a new standard emerged which combined the best of the TTL family with the advantages of the CD4000 family.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] It was known as the 74HC (which used anywhere from 3.3V to 5V power supplies (and used logic levels relative to the power supply)), and with devices that used 5V power supplies and TTL logic levels.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] The letters "HC" stand for "High-speed CMOS".
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] TTL logic levels are different from those of CMOS – generally a TTL output does not rise high enough to be reliably recognized as a logic 1 by a CMOS input.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] This problem was solved by the invention of the 74HCT family of devices that uses CMOS technology but TTL input logic levels.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] These devices only work with a 5V power supply.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] They form a replacement for TTL, although HCT is slower than original TTL (HC logic has about the same speed as original TTL).
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] Other CMOS circuit families within integrated circuits include cascode voltage switch logic (CVSL) and pass transistor logic (PTL) of various sorts.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] These are generally used "on-chip" and are not delivered as building-block medium-scale or small-scale integrated circuits.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] One major improvement was to combine CMOS inputs and TTL drivers to form of a new type of logic devices called BiCMOS logic, of which the LVT and ALVT logic families are the most important.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] The BiCMOS family has many members, including ABT logic, ALB logic, ALVT logic, BCT logic and LVT logic.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] With HC and HCT logic and LS-TTL logic competing in the market it became clear that further improvements were needed to create the *ideal* logic device that combined high speed, with low power dissipation and compatibility with older logic families.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] A whole range of newer families has emerged that use CMOS technology.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] There are many others including AC/ACT logic, AHC/AHCT logic, ALVC logic, AUC logic, AVC logic, CBT logic, CBTLV logic, FCT logic and LVC logic (LVCMOS).
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] The integrated injection logic (IIL or I2L) uses bipolar transistors in a current-steering arrangement to implement logic functions.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] It was used in some integrated circuits, but it is now considered obsolete.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] The following logic families would either have been used to build up systems from functional blocks such as flip-flops, counters, and gates, or else would be used as "glue" logic to interconnect very-large scale integration devices such as memory and processors.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] Not shown are some early obscure logic families from the early 1960s such as DCTL (direct-coupled transistor logic), which did not become widely available.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] Several techniques and design styles are primarily used in designing large single-chip application-specific integrated circuits (ASIC) and CPUs, rather than generic logic families intended for use in multi-chip applications.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] These design styles can typically be divided into two main categories, static techniques and clocked dynamic techniques.
[src:level-shifters/logic-family] (See static versus dynamic logic for some discussion on the advantages and disadvantages of each category).
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] In digital circuits, a **logic level** is one of a finite number of states that a digital signal can inhabit.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] Logic levels are usually represented by the voltage difference between the signal and ground, although other standards exist.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] The range of voltage levels that represent each state depends on the logic family being used.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] A *logic-level shifter* can be used to allow compatibility between different circuits.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] In binary logic the two levels are **logical high** and **logical low**, which generally correspond to binary numbers 1 and 0 respectively or truth values *true* and *false* respectively.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] Signals with one of these two levels can be used in Boolean algebra for digital circuit design or analysis.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] The use of either the higher or the lower voltage level to represent either logic state is arbitrary.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] The two options are **active high** (*positive logic*) and **active low** (*negative logic*).
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] Active-high and active-low states can be mixed at will: for example, a read only memory integrated circuit may have a chip-select signal that is active-low, but the data and address bits are conventionally active-high.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] Occasionally a logic design is simplified by inverting the choice of active level (see De Morgan's laws).
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] The name of an active-low signal is historically written with a bar above it to distinguish it from an active-high signal.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] For example, the name Q, read *Q bar* or *Q not*, represents an active-low signal.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] Many control signals in electronics are active-low signals (usually reset lines, chip-select lines and so on).
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] Logic families such as TTL can sink more current than they can source, so fanout and noise immunity increase.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] It also allows for wired-OR logic if the logic gates are open-collector/open-drain with a pull-up resistor.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] Examples of this are the I²C bus, CAN bus, and PCI bus.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] Some signals have a meaning in both states and notation may indicate such.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] For example, it is common to have a read/write line designated R/W, indicating that the signal is high in case of a read and low in case of a write.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] The two logical states are usually represented by two different voltages, but two different currents are used in some logic signaling, like digital current loop interface and current-mode logic.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] High and low thresholds are specified for each logic family.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] When below the low threshold, the signal is *low*.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] When above the high threshold, the signal is *high*.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] Intermediate levels are undefined, resulting in highly implementation-specific circuit behavior.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] It is usual to allow some tolerance in the voltage levels used; for example, 0 to 2 volts might represent logic 0, and 3 to 5 volts logic 1.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] A voltage of 2 to 3 volts would be invalid and occur only in a fault condition or during a logic-level transition.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] However, few logic circuits can detect such a condition, and most devices will interpret the signal simply as high or low in an undefined or device-specific manner.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] Some logic devices incorporate Schmitt trigger inputs, whose behavior is much better defined in the threshold region and have increased resilience to small variations in the input voltage.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] The problem of the circuit designer is to avoid circumstances that produce intermediate levels, so that the circuit behaves predictably.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] Nearly all digital circuits use a consistent logic level for all internal signals.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] That level, however, varies from one system to another.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] Interconnecting any two logic families often required special techniques such as additional pull-up resistors or purpose-built interface circuits known as level shifters.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] A level shifter connects one digital circuit that uses one logic level to another digital circuit that uses another logic level.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] Often two level shifters are used, one at each system: A line driver converts from internal logic levels to standard interface line levels; a line receiver converts from interface levels to internal voltage levels.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] For example, TTL levels are different from those of CMOS.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] Generally, a TTL output does not rise high enough to be reliably recognized as a logic 1 by a CMOS input, especially if it is only connected to a high-input-impedance CMOS input that does not source significant current.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] These devices only work with a 5 V power supply.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] Though rare, ternary computers evaluate base 3 three-valued or ternary logic using 3 voltage levels.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] In three-state logic, an output device can be in one of three possible states: 0, 1, or Z, with the last meaning high impedance.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] This is not a voltage or logic level, but means that the output is not controlling the state of the connected circuit.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] Four-valued logic adds a fourth state, X (*don't care*), meaning the value of the signal is unimportant and undefined.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] It means that an input is undefined, or an output signal may be chosen for implementation convenience (see Karnaugh map § Don't cares).
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] IEEE 1164 defines 9 logic states for use in electronic design automation.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] The standard includes strong and weakly driven signals, high impedance and unknown and uninitialized states.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] In solid-state storage devices, a multi-level cell stores data using multiple voltages.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] Storing n bits in one cell requires the device to reliably distinguish 2n distinct voltage levels.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] Digital line codes may use more than two states to encode and transmit data more efficiently.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] Examples include alternate mark inversion and 4B3T from telecommunications, and pulse-amplitude modulation variants used by Ethernet over twisted pair.
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] For instance, 100BASE-TX uses MLT-3 encoding with three differential voltage levels (−1V, 0V, +1V) while 1000BASE-T encodes data using five differential voltage levels (−1V, −0.5V, 0V, +0.5V, +1V).
[src:level-shifters/logic-level] Once received, the line coding is converted back to binary.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] These open outputs configurations are often used for digital applications when the transistor acts as a switch, to allow for logic-level conversion, wired-logic connections, and line sharing.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] External pull-up/down resistors are typically required to set the output during the Hi-Z state to a specific voltage.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] Analog applications include analog weighting, summing, limiting, and digital-to-analog converters.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] The NPN BJT (n-type bipolar junction transistor) and nMOS (n-type metal oxide semiconductor field effect transistor) have greater conductance than their PNP and pMOS relatives, so may be more commonly used for these outputs.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] Open outputs using PNP and pMOS transistors will use the opposite internal voltage rail used by NPN and nMOS transistors.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] An **open collector output** processes an IC's output through the base of an internal bipolar junction transistor (BJT), whose collector is exposed as the external output pin.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] The output is usually connected to an external pull-up resistor, which pulls the output voltage to the resistor's supply voltage when the transistor is off.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] For PNP open collector outputs, the emitter of the PNP transistor is internally connected to the positive voltage rail, so the collector outputs a high voltage when the transistor is on or is hi-Z when off.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] This is sometimes called "open collector, drives high".
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] For an NPN open emitter output, the collector is connected to the positive voltage rail, so the emitter outputs a high voltage when the transistor is on and is hi-Z when off.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] For a PNP open emitter output, the collector is connected to the low voltage supply, so the emitter outputs a low voltage when the transistor is on and is hi-Z when off.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] An nMOS open drain output connects to ground when a high voltage is applied to the MOSFET's gate, or presents a high impedance when a low voltage is applied to the gate.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] The voltage in this high impedance state would be *floating* (undefined) because the MOSFET is not conducting, which is why nMOS open drain outputs require a pull-up resistor connected to a positive voltage rail for producing a high output voltage.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] Microelectronic devices using nMOS open drain output may provide a 'weak' (high-resistance, often on the order of 100 kΩ) internal pull-up resistor to connect the terminal in question to the positive power supply of the device so their output voltage doesn't float.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] Such weak pullups reduce power consumption due to their lower $V^{2}/R$ ohmic heating and possibly avoid the need for an external pull-up.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] External pullups may be 'stronger' (lower resistance, perhaps 3 kΩ) to reduce signal rise times (like with I²C) or to minimize noise (like on system RESET inputs).
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] Modern microcontrollers may allow programming particular output pins to use open drain instead of push–pull output, the strength of the internal pull-up, and allow disabling internal pullups when not desired.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] For pMOS open drain, the output instead connects to the positive power rail when the transistor is on, and is hi-Z when off.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] This is sometimes called "open drain, drives high".
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] For a nMOS open source output, the drain is internally connected to the positive voltage rail, so the source outputs a high voltage when the transistor is on and is hi-Z when off.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] For a pMOS open source output, the drain is internally connected to the low voltage rail, so the output instead connects to the low voltage rail when the transistor is on, or is hi-Z when off.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] ⎐ – NPN open collector or similar output that can supply a relatively low-impedance low voltage when not turned off.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] Capable of positive-logic wired-AND connection.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] ⎏ – NPN open emitter or similar output that can supply a relatively low-impedance high voltage when not turned off.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] Capable of positive-logic wired-OR connection.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] ⎑ – variant with an internal pull-down resistor to provide a low voltage when off.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] Note: this section primarily deals with npn open collectors, however nMOS open drain generally applies as well.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] Because the pull-up resistor is external and does not need to be connected to the chip supply voltage, a lower or higher voltage than the chip supply voltage can be used instead (provided it does not exceed the absolute maximum rating of the chip's output).
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] Open outputs are therefore sometimes used to interface different families of devices that have different operating voltage levels.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] The open collector transistor can be rated to withstand a higher voltage than the chip supply voltage.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] This technique is commonly used by logic circuits operating at 5 V or lower to drive higher voltage devices such as electric motors, LEDs in series, 12 V relays, 50 V vacuum fluorescent displays, or Nixie tubes requiring more than 100 V.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] Another advantage is that more than one open-collector output can be connected to a single line.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] If all open collector outputs attached to a line are off (i.e. in the high-impedance state), the pull-up resistor will be the only device setting the line's voltage and will pull the line voltage high.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] But if one or more open-collector outputs attached to the line are on (i.e. conducting to ground), since any one of them are strong enough to overcome the pull-up resistor's limited ability to hold the voltage high, the line voltage will instead be pulled low.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] This wired logic connection has several uses.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] By tying the output of several open collectors together and connecting to a pull-up resistor, the common line becomes a *wired AND* in active high logic.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] The output will be high (true) only when all gates are in the high-impedance state, and will be low (false) otherwise, like Boolean AND.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] When treated as active-low logic, this behaves like Boolean OR, since the output is low (true) when any input is low.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] See Transistor–transistor logic § Open collector wired logic.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] Line sharing is used for interrupts and buses (such as I²C or 1-Wire).
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] Open-collector output enables one active device to drive the shared line without interference from the other inactive devices.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] If push–pull output was mistakenly used **instead**, the active device attempting to set the line voltage low would be in competition with the other devices attempting to set the line voltage high, which would result in unpredictable output and heat.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] SCSI-1 devices use open collector for electrical signaling.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] Open collector outputs can also be useful for analog weighting, summing, limiting, digital-to-analog converters, etc., but such applications are not discussed here.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] One problem such open-collector and similar devices with a pull-up resistor is the resistor consumes power constantly while the output is low.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] Higher operating speeds require lower resistor values for faster pull-up, which consume even more power.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] Also when driving a load, current through the pull-up resistor reduces the output high voltage by a voltage drop equal to the current times resistance, according to Ohm's law.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] JEDEC standardized the terms POD15, POD125, POD135, and POD12 for 1.5 V, 1.25 V, 1.35 V, and 1.2 V interface supply voltages respectively.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] DDR4 memory uses POD12 drivers but with the same driver strength (34 Ω/48 Ω) for pull-down (RonPd) and pull-up (RonPu).
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] The term POD in DDR4 referring only for termination type that is only parallel pull-up without the pull-down termination at the far end.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] The reference point (VREF) for the input is not half-supply as was in DDR3 and may be higher.
[src:level-shifters/open-collector] A comparison of both DDR3 and DDR4 termination schemes in terms of skew, eye aperture and power consumption was published in late 2011.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] In electronics, a **voltage divider** (also known as a **potential divider**) is a passive linear circuit that produces an output voltage (*V*out) that is a fraction of its input voltage (*V*in).
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] **Voltage division** is the result of distributing the input voltage among the components of the divider.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] A simple example of a voltage divider is two resistors connected in series, with the input voltage applied across the resistor pair and the output voltage emerging from the connection between them.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] Resistor voltage dividers are commonly used to create reference voltages, or to reduce the magnitude of a voltage so it can be measured, and may also be used as signal attenuators at low alternating current frequencies.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] In electric power transmission, a capacitive voltage divider is used for measurement of high voltage.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] A voltage divider referenced to ground is created by connecting two electrical impedances in series, as shown in Figure 1.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] The input voltage is applied across the series impedances *Z*1 and *Z*2 and the output is the voltage across *Z*2.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] *Z*1 and *Z*2 may be composed of any combination of elements such as resistors, inductors and capacitors.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] In general this transfer function is a complex, rational function of frequency.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] A resistive divider is the case where both impedances, *Z*1 and *Z*2, are purely resistive (Figure 2).
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] and by solving using algebra, *R*2 must be twice the value of *R*1.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] Any ratio *V*out / *V*in greater than 1 is not possible.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] That is, using resistors alone it is not possible to either invert the voltage or increase *V*out above *V*in.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] Consider a divider consisting of a resistor and capacitor as shown in Figure 3.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] where *X*C is the reactance of the capacitor, *C* is the capacitance of the capacitor, *j* is the imaginary unit, and *ω* (omega) is the radian frequency of the input voltage.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] The product *τ* (tau) = *RC* is called the *time constant* of the circuit.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] The ratio then depends on frequency, in this case decreasing as frequency increases.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] This circuit is, in fact, a basic (first-order) low-pass filter.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] The ratio contains an imaginary number, and actually contains both the amplitude and phase shift information of the filter.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] The above equation is for non-interacting inductors; mutual inductance (as in an autotransformer) will alter the results.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] Inductive dividers split AC input according to the reactance of the elements as for the resistive divider above.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] Capacitive dividers do not pass DC input.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] Any leakage current in the capactive elements requires use of the generalized expression with two impedances.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] By selection of parallel *R* and *C* elements in the proper proportions, the same division ratio can be maintained over a useful range of frequencies.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] This is the principle applied in compensated oscilloscope probes to increase measurement bandwidth.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] The output voltage of a voltage divider will vary according to the electric current it is supplying to its external electrical load.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] The effective source impedance coming from a divider of *Z*1 and *Z*2, as above, will be *Z*1 in parallel with *Z*2 (sometimes written *Z*1 || *Z*2), that is: (*Z*1 *Z*2) / (*Z*1 + *Z*2) = *HZ*1.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] To obtain a sufficiently stable output voltage, the output current must either be stable (and so be made part of the calculation of the potential divider values) or limited to an appropriately small percentage of the divider's input current.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] Load sensitivity can be decreased by reducing the impedance of both halves of the divider, though this increases the divider's quiescent input current and results in higher power consumption (and wasted heat) in the divider.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] Voltage regulators are often used in lieu of passive voltage dividers when it is necessary to accommodate high or fluctuating load currents.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] Voltage dividers are used for adjusting the level of a signal, for bias of active devices in amplifiers, and for measurement of voltages.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] A Wheatstone bridge and a multimeter both include voltage dividers.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] A potentiometer is used as a variable voltage divider in the volume control of many radios.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] Voltage dividers can be used to allow a microcontroller to measure the resistance of a sensor.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] The sensor is wired in series with a known resistance to form a voltage divider and a known voltage is applied across the divider.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] The microcontroller's analog-to-digital converter is connected to the center tap of the divider so that it can measure the tap voltage and, by using the measured voltage and the known resistance and voltage, compute the sensor resistance.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] This technique is commonly used to measure the resistance of temperature sensors such as thermistors and RTDs.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] Another example that is commonly used involves a potentiometer (variable resistor) as one of the resistive elements.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] When the shaft of the potentiometer is rotated the resistance it produces either increases or decreases, the change in resistance corresponds to the angular change of the shaft.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] If coupled with a stable voltage reference, the output voltage can be fed into an analog-to-digital converter and a display can show the angle.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] Such circuits are commonly used in reading control knobs.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] A voltage divider can be used to scale down a very high voltage so that it can be measured by a volt meter.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] The high voltage is applied across the divider, and the divider output—which outputs a lower voltage that is within the meter's input range—is measured by the meter.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] High voltage resistor divider probes designed specifically for this purpose can be used to measure voltages up to 100 kV.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] Special high-voltage resistors are used in such probes as they must be able to tolerate high input voltages and, to produce accurate results, must have matched temperature coefficients and very low voltage coefficients.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] Capacitive divider probes are typically used for voltages above 100 kV, as the heat caused by power losses in resistor divider probes at such high voltages could be excessive.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] A voltage divider can be used as a crude logic level shifter to interface two circuits that use different operating voltages.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] For example, some logic circuits operate at 5 V whereas others operate at 3.3 V.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] Directly interfacing a 5 V logic output to a 3.3 V input may cause permanent damage to the 3.3 V circuit.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] In this case, a voltage divider with an output ratio of 3.3/5 might be used to reduce the 5 V signal to 3.3 V, to allow the circuits to interoperate without damaging the 3.3 V circuit.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] For this to be feasible, the 5 V source impedance and 3.3 V input impedance must be negligible, or they must be constant and the divider resistor values must account for their impedances.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] If the input impedance is capacitive, a purely resistive divider will limit the data rate.
[src:level-shifters/voltage-divider] This can be roughly overcome by adding a capacitor in series with the top resistor, to make both legs of the divider capacitive as well as resistive.
